Work is underway to find a route to commercialising the novel turbulence probe.</gtr:description><gtr:firstYearOfImpact>2016</gtr:firstYearOfImpact><gtr:id>E1AA5C1E-8027-4C65-8113-B7EFC467BD9D</gtr:id><gtr:impactTypes><gtr:impactType>Societal,Economic</gtr:impactType></gtr:impactTypes><gtr:outcomeId>56e073128a9549.96734719</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Energy</gtr:sector></gtr:impactSummaryOutput></gtr:impactSummaryOutputs><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>All three of the high level project objectives have been achieved: 1. We have understood how sea turbulence effects the unsteady loads experienced by tidal turbines. 2. We have successfully developed methods of reducing this unsteady loading at source. 3. We have demonstrated these technologies on a model turbine in large scale water tunnel trials. 
A number of specific discoveries have been made: 1. Unsteady torque and thrust on the turbine can be reduced using blade-mounted 'load shedding' devices. These were tested in a wind tunnel and then in a scale model of a tidal turbine at IFREMER, France. A side-benefit from these tests has been the development of techniques for underwater communication using wireless telemetry. 2. The turbine control system and drivetrain can also be altered to reduce fatigue loads. A scale model turbine with constant torque and constant rpm controllers was used to test the impact of different levels of inertia in the drivetrain and reductions in loading were achieved. 3. The state-of-the-art methods of measuring gusts at sea have been found to be inadequate and an alternative device (based on aerospace technology) has been developed. 4. A novel turbulence model for use in LES simulations has been developed and tested.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>1. The load shedding devices which have been developed can be used by the tidal turbine industry to reduce unsteady loading. 2. The turbulence model can be used by others in their simulations of tidal turbines under unsteady conditions 3. Commercial exploitation of the novel measurement device is being explored, and a grant application for sea trials is in progress. This would enable the industry to buy cheap devices which are capable of measuring sea turbulence. Currently available methods are expensive and can't measure the lower length scale turbulence. 4. Methods for the use of wireless telemetry for underwater communication have been published so that others can use these techniques in a wide range of applications.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>02CD781B-F85C-4331-B22E-A5DC3D4C79D7</gtr:id><gtr:outcomeId>56e072067e6b53.62940480</gtr:outcomeId><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Aerospace, Defence and Marine,Energy,Environment</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/